<exercises xml:id="exercises-relations">
<title>Exercises</title>

<!-- TODO check against Roman -->

<!-- TODO: determine properties of relation just by looking at graph. -->

<exercisegroup xml:id="exercisegroup-relations-draw-graph">
	<title>Directed graph for a relation</title>

	<introduction><p>
		In each of
		<xref ref="exercisegroup-relations-draw-graph" text="type-local">Exercises</xref>,
		you are given a relation on a specific set.
		Draw a directed graph that represents the relation.
	</p></introduction>

	<exercise><p> Relation <m> \mathord{\subsetneqq} </m> on <m> \powset{\{a,b,c\}} </m>. </p></exercise>

	<exercise><p> Relation <m> \mathord{\lt} </m> on <m> \{1,2,3,4\} </m>. </p></exercise>

	<exercise><p> Relation <m> \mathord{\equiv_3} </m> on <m> \natnumlt{13} </m>. </p></exercise>

	<exercise><p>
		Relation <q>has the same number of occurrences of the letter <m> \mathrm{a} </m> as</q>
		on <m> \words{\Sigma}_4 </m> for alphabet <m> \Sigma = \{\mathrm{a}, \mathrm{z}\} </m>.
	</p></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercise><p>   <!-- TODO \refAdapt{hunter+discrete}{2.4}{13} -->
	Recall that a relation on a set <m> A </m> is just a subset of the Cartesian product <m> A \cartprod A </m>.
	Write out all relations on the set <m> A = \{a,b\} </m> as subsets of <m> A \cartprod A </m>.
	Which of these relations are reflexive? Symmetric? Antisymmetric? Transitive?
</p></exercise>

<exercisegroup xml:id="exercisegroup-relations-determine-properties">
	<title>Testing reflexivity/symmetry/antisymmetry/transitivity</title>

	<introduction><p>
		In each of
		<xref ref="exercisegroup-relations-determine-properties" text="type-local">Exercises</xref>,
		you are given a relation on a specific set.
		Determine which of the properties
		<term><xref ref="definition-relations-reflexive" text="title" /></term>,
		<term><xref ref="definition-relations-symmetric" text="title" /></term>,
		<term><xref ref="definition-relations-antisymmetric" text="title" /></term>, and
		<term><xref ref="definition-relations-transitive" text="title" /></term>
		the given relation possesses.
	</p></introduction>

	<exercise><p> Relation <m> \mathord{\lt} </m> on <m> \R </m>. </p></exercise>

	<exercise><p> Relation <m> \mathord{\ge} </m> on <m> \R </m>. </p></exercise>

	<exercise><p> Relation <m> \mathord{\mid} </m> on <m> \Z </m>. </p></exercise>

	<exercise><p>
		Relation <m> \mathord{\subseteq} </m> on <m> \powset{X} </m>,
		where <m> X </m> is an arbitrary, unspecified set.
	</p></exercise>

	<exercise><p>
		Relation <q>is taller than</q> on the set of all living humans.
	</p></exercise>

	<exercise><p>
		Relation <q>is parallel to</q> on the set of all straight lines in the plane.
	</p></exercise>

	<exercise><p>
		Relation <q>is perpendicular to</q> on the set of all straight lines in the plane.
	</p></exercise>

	<exercise><p>
		Relation <q>has the same length as</q> on <m> \words{\Sigma} </m>,
		where <m> \Sigma </m> is an arbitrary, unspecified alphabet set.
	</p></exercise>

	<exercise><p>
		Relation <q>is shorter than</q> on <m> \words{\Sigma} </m>,
		where <m> \Sigma </m> is an arbitrary, unspecified alphabet set.
	</p></exercise>

	<exercise><p>
		Relation <q>contains the same number of occurrences of the letter <m> x </m> as</q> on <m> \words{\Sigma} </m>,
		where <m> \Sigma </m> is an arbitrary, unspecified alphabet set and <m> x </m> is some fixed choice of letter in <m> \Sigma </m>.
	</p></exercise>

	<exercise><p>
		Relation <m> \mathord{\lgcequiv} </m> on the set of all logical statements involving the statement variables
		<m> p_1,p_2,p_3,\dotsc </m>.
	</p></exercise>

	<exercise><p>
		Relation <m> R </m> defined by <q><m> a_1 \mathrel{R} a_2 </m> if <m> f(a_1) = f(a_2) </m></q> on a set <m> A </m>,
		where <m> \funcdef{f}{A}{B} </m> is an arbitrary, unspecified function.
	</p></exercise>

</exercisegroup>

<exercisegroup xml:id="exercisegroup-relations-draw-graph-with-properties">
	<title>Properties of relations reflected in their graphs</title>

	<introduction><p>
		In each of
		<xref ref="exercisegroup-relations-draw-graph-with-properties" text="type-local">Exercises</xref>,
		you are given a list of properties.
		Draw the directed graph of a relation on the set <m> \{a,b,c,d\} </m> that possesses the given properties.
	</p></introduction>

	<exercise><p>
		Symmetric and transitive, but neither reflexive nor antisymmetric.
	</p></exercise>

	<exercise><p>
		Reflexive, antisymmetric, and transitive, but not symmetric.
	</p></exercise>

</exercisegroup>

<exercise><p> Prove that a relation is symmetric if and only if it is equivalent to its own inverse relation. </p></exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-relations-prove-antisymmetric-test-option"><p>
	As described in <xref ref="section-relations-properties" />,
	the definition of <term><xref ref="definition-relations-antisymmetric" text="title" /> relation</term>
	can be formulated in symbolic language as
	<!-- <md> (\forall a_1 \in A)(\forall a_2 \in A)({a_1 \neq a_2} \lgcimplies {{a_1 \not\mathrel{R} a_2} \lgcor {a_2 \not\mathrel{R} a_1}}) </md>. -->
	<md> (\forall a_1 \in A)(\forall a_2 \in A)({a_1 \neq a_2} \lgcimplies {{a_1\ \not R\ a_2} \lgcor {a_2\ \not R\ a_1}}) </md>.
	Prove that each of the two conditionals provided in the
	<xref ref="test-relations-antisymmetric" text="custom">Antisymmetric Relation Test</xref>
	are equivalent to the symbolic formulation of the definition of antisymmetric given above.
</p></exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-relations-symm-antisymm-equality"><p>
	Suppose <m> R </m> is a relation on a set <m> A </m> that is both symmetric and antisymmetric.
	Prove that <m> R </m> is a subset of the identity relation <m> \setdef{(x,x)}{x \in A} </m>.
</p></exercise>

</exercises>
